[1] _Botrytis_, grapevine - Australia (New South Wales)
Date: Mon 3 Mar 2008
Source: Mudgee Guardian [edited]
<http://mudgee.yourguide.com.au/news/local/general/a-lot-of-rot/1194458.html>


Drenching rain over Mudgee has rejuvenated much of the landscape this
summer and eased the drought considerably, but it has spelt trouble
for the region's vineyards. The wet and humid conditions have
provided an ideal breeding ground for botrytis, or bunch rot.

David Lowe from Lowe Family Wines said while some vineyards have been
badly affected, others have managed to remain clean. Some varieties
are proving hardier than others. Mr Lowe said the grape varieties
that are thin-skinned, such as semillon and merlot, have suffered the
most, while the cabernet sauvignon grapes are standing up well. The
older vines in the area have also held up against the disease because
the grape bunches are dense, which lowers the chance of attack. Mr
Lowe said there will be losses as a result of the botrytis.

Mudgee Wine Grape Growers Association executive officer Mike O'Malley
said while botrytis is prevalent, the incidence varies widely and
those who have maintained good vineyard maintenance and spray regime
are in better standing. In some cases botrytis is known as 'noble
rot', which occurs when drier conditions follow rain and is used for
creating sweet desert wines.

[Byline: Cassie Hough]

