******
[2] Fungal diseases, grapevine - Australia (New South Wales)
Date: Fri 29 Feb 2008
Source: The Singleton Argus [edited]
<http://singleton.yourguide.com.au/news/local/general/grapes-left-to-rot-on-the-vines/1193281.html>


Much of the red wine grapes have been left rotting on the vines in
the local Hunter winegrowing region as producers have struggled with
a wet growing season topped off by an even wetter January [2008]. The
rain couldn't have come at a worse time for red wine producers with
January rainfall adding insult in the crucial build-up to the harvest
in what has already been a difficult vintage, with as much as half of
the season's crop lost to disease.

Bruce Tyrrell, spokesperson for the Hunter Valley Winegrower's
Association, who has more than 40 years experience in the local
industry said it was a season reminiscent of the latter part of the
60's and early 70s. "There has been 50 inches of rain since the June
[2007] long weekend, and even with the rain there has not been a day
over 35 degrees," he said. "Now much of the crops are going to waste."

Hope Estate's Michael Hope said what had made the season so difficult
had been getting enough sunshine to ripen the reds and the disease
pressure from the rain.

