******
[3] Fungal diseases, grapevine - South Africa
Date: Fri 29 Feb 2008
Source: South African Wine [edited]
<http://www.wine.co.za/news/news.aspx?NEWSID=11378&Source=News>


Harvest 2008 is in full swing. Most of the regions are experiencing
the effect of our summer rains but, so far, it does not appear as if
it will affect the quality of the 2008 wines.

Constantia: the recent rains have resulted in some fungal disease.

Franschhoek: rain has increased disease pressures from powdery mildew
and botrytis; the biggest challenge will be to pick fully ripe grapes
that are also healthy.

Hemel En Aarde Valley: fungal disease is under control; managing
botrytis and other fungal growth remains the challenge.

Paarl: to combat fungal rot, excess leaves from underneath and within
the canopy are being removed so the wind will dry off moisture.

Robertson: has not escaped untimely rain, which for some requires
money and effort to combat mildew and botrytis.

Stellenbosch: canopy management has been vital, and fungal
disease-prone varieties have survived; everything is "on a knife
edge."

Worcester: the unseasonal rain has brought many challenges: botrytis,
excessive growth resulting from the increased nitrogen after the
thunder storms, and delayed picking, which will cause a bottle neck
in the cellars; some crop loss due to botrytis and dilution.

Klein Karoo, Durbanville, Olifants River, Swartland: so far, minimal
or no negative effects from the rains.

[Byline: Angela Lloyd]

