[_Botrytis_ bunch rot
---------------------
Bunch rot caused by the fungus _Botrytis cinerea_ has been reported
wherever grapes are grown. The disease can cause serious losses in
both yield and fruit quality. The fungus infects shoots, flowers,
leaves, and fruit. If blossoms are infected, the fungus remains
latent until berries begin to soften. Infection is optimal at 15-20
deg C (59-68 deg F) with free water or over 90 percent humidity.
Grape cultivars with dense canopies, thin skins, and/or tight
clusters are more susceptible. The rot may progress to infect whole
clusters, and girdling lesions on the pedicel or rachis may lead to
drying and premature cluster drop. Affected berries may split open,
develop a grayish mold on the surface, and may shrivel in dry
conditions. The pathogen overwinters on plant material and is spread
by water, wind, mechanical means, and juice from split berries.
Mechanical damage caused by birds or insects creates entry points for
the fungus and can greatly increase losses. Disease management relies
mainly on fungicide applications and cultural practices.

_B. cinerea_ also causes blights and grey molds on a range of other
crops, for example onion, peanut, mango, and tomato.

Powdery mildew
--------------
Powdery mildew of grapevine is caused by the fungus _Erysiphe
necator_. Leaves heavily infected by powdery mildew have reduced
photosynthetic ability resulting in decreased plant vigour and
increased chance of winter injury to the vines. Spores are spread to
the leaves and berries mainly by splashing rain, wind, or mechanical
means. The fungus overwinters in infected leaves on the ground. The
disease can be extremely serious and will cause severe crop losses.
It is usually controlled with fungicides.

Powdery mildews are a group of fungi causing similar symptoms on a
range of host plants. The group includes many species in a number of
genera. Generally, each fungal species is confined to a number of
host species it affects. The pathogens cause serious losses in many
important crops including cereals, hops, canola, sugar beet, and a
number of vegetable crops.

